> Black garlic is traditionally used in Asian cuisine and is made by heating whole bulbs of garlic over the course of several weeks, a process that results in black cloves. The taste is sweet and syrupy with hints of balsamic vinegar or tamarind, which makes it the perfect ingredient for our sweet and sticky teriyaki sauce.

Boil a #medium sized pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Once boiling add your @egg noodle nest{3} for ~{4%mins}.

Chop the bottom 3cm from the @asparagus{2} and discard. Now chop the asparagus widthways into three pieces. ~{90%seconds} before the noodles are finished add the asparagus into the boiling noodle water.

Peel the @ginger{2}(peeled and finely chopped) with the edge of a #spoon{} and very finely chop. Mix the @black garlic teriyaki sauce{4} in a #cup{} with @water{3%tbsp} and keep to the side.

Drain the noodles and asparagus in a #sieve{} or #colander{}. Refill the #pot{} with cold water and put the noodles and asparagus back in. Leave to the side for later.

Very, very thinly slice the @Roaming Roosters pork fillet{600%g} and toss it in the @cornflour{2%tbsp} with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch}. Heat 1 tbsp of @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on high heat. Once it's really hot (but not smoking) add in the pork and quickly brown off on both sides (discard any excess cornflour).

> If you only have a small pan then cook it off in batches. Overcrowding the pan won't give you a nice caramelised finish.

Once the pork is browned off on both sides remove it from the pan and keep to the side. Heat the @sesame oil{1} in the pan on medium-high heat and once it's hot add the ginger for ~{30%seconds}.

Add back the pork with the teriyaki sauce and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the drained noodles and asparagus to the pork. Cook for ~{1%minute} then serve it with a scattering of @sesame seeds{1}.